The Kubernetes Crusade: Workshop on Defending & Attacking Kubernetes

Lab: Network Security Policies - Blocking Ingress Traffic Based on Source Pod Labels

Lab Objective

  • Two namespaces, 'namespace-a' and 'namespace-b', are created. Each namespace houses an 'nginx' pod, named 'app-a' and 'app-b' respectively.
  • After confirming initial connectivity between 'app-a' and 'app-b', a Network Policy is implemented in 'namespace-b' that blocks ingress traffic from any pods with the label 'app: app-a'.
  • When attempting to connect from 'app-a' to 'app-b' again, the request should timeout, demonstrating the effective blocking of the Network Policy. Lastly, the lab concludes with cleaning up the created namespaces.

Open New Terminal (Optional)

If current working directory is not workspace/.

  • Click on + icon, then select new terminal to open new terminal.

  • Keep current working directory as workspace/ and change the directory as mentioned below.
cd course/7_protection_strategies/7.1_network_policies
ls

  • Look into the demo nsp policy.
cat deny_ns2_to_ns1.yaml
  • Deny all ingress traffic from namespaces labeled as "ns2" to all pods in the "ns1" namespace.
  • apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1: This line specifies the API version that is used for creating the NetworkPolicy resource.
  • kind: NetworkPolicy: Specifies the kind of resource to be created, which in this case is a NetworkPolicy.
  • metadata: Under this, name: deny-ns2 and namespace: ns1 defines the metadata for the NetworkPolicy, where the name of the NetworkPolicy is "deny-ns2" and it's being created in the "ns1" namespace.
  • spec: podSelector: {} means the policy applies to all pods in namespace "ns1". policyTypes: - Ingress indicates that the rules in this policy apply to incoming (ingress) traffic.
  • ingress: from: and namespaceSelector: with matchLabels: name: ns2 means allow incoming connections from any pod in namespaces that have the label "name: ns2". However, as there are no specific ports defined, this effectively denies all incoming traffic from namespace "ns2" to "ns1".

Blocking Ingress Traffic Based on Source Pod Labels

  • Create the namespaces for network testing.
kubectl create namespace namespace-a
kubectl create namespace namespace-b

  • Create the applications 
kubectl run app-a --image=nginx --namespace=namespace-a --port=80 --labels=app=app-a
kubectl expose pod app-a --namespace=namespace-a --port=80 --type=ClusterIP
kubectl run app-b --image=nginx --namespace=namespace-b --port=80 --labels=app=app-b
kubectl expose pod app-b --namespace=namespace-b --port=80 --type=ClusterIP

  • Before applying the Network Policy, test the connectivity from the app-a to app-b.
kubectl run --namespace=namespace-a --rm -i -t curl --image=radial/busyboxplus:curl --restart=Never -- wget -qO- --timeout=2 app-b.namespace-b.svc.cluster.local

  • This Network Policy will block all traffic to pods in namespace-b with the label app: app-b from pods with the label app: app-a.
# Network Policy
cat <<EOF | kubectl apply -f -
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: NetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: deny-app-a
  namespace: namespace-b
spec:
  podSelector:
    matchLabels:
      app: app-b
  policyTypes:
  - Ingress
  ingress:
  - from:
    - podSelector:
        matchLabels:
          app: app-a
EOF

  • Try to access app-b from app-a again.

This time, the request should time out, indicating that the Network Policy is blocking the traffic.

kubectl run --namespace=namespace-a --rm -i -t curl --image=radial/busyboxplus:curl --restart=Never -- wget -qO- --timeout=2 app-b.namespace-b.svc.cluster.local

  • Cleanup: let's clean up the resources we created.
kubectl delete namespaces namespace-a namespace-b
